life is messy. life is heartbreakingüíî at times. there are moments of pain that brings us to our knees. there are consequences to decisions that we never expected. we can make horrible decisions. our lives can change in an instant. grief can hit us like a freight train. we fail. and fail. and fail. .

column2: we have a question to ask ourselves:

column1: do i #overcome this or succumb to this‚ùì
as someone that lived in #fear or #shame or #anxiety for so many years
column2: i can say that the easy thing to do is toss in the towel. to whine
column4: and use that moment to justify future poor decisions. and if i‚Äôm being honest
column5: i have adopted the victim #mentality before. but what i have learned in the last decade especially is that we are never a victim unless we allow it.

column1: god walks ahead of us. he fights our battles. he gives us #strength. he carries us in his arms. he gathers our tears. we are #victorious with him. we know that this hard season will pass
column2: and we will appreciate those sunny days and laughter and love that much more.üîÜüíó

column1: i can also now appreciate allllll the #mistakes
column3: disappointment and failures because it makes me more able to relate to people. #divorce
column10: mistakes..... there‚Äôs not a lot that i can‚Äôt #empathize with. it is these experiences that allow us to truly connect with others. what a comfort it is
column12: to have someone come along side of you
column14: and say ‚Äúi get it‚Äù. i praise god for those people.

column1: 52131;instagram;2019-02-01 13:37:57;FALSE;"üíñ link in bio üíñ gillette‚Äôs recent advert
column2: we believe: the best men can be
column6: a necessary step towards bringing men-specific issues into the mainstream. it immediately went viral
column7: accumulating more than 4 million youtube views in 48 hours and polarising opinion in the biggest divide since brexit.

column1: but with all the back and forth over whether or not the messaging was right
column2: we aren't addressing the real issue with the advert. what we should be questioning is whether or not it was a brand's place to get involved in that conversation at all
column3: and by that i mean their needless inclusion of #metoo
column4: which was included seemingly for no reason other than to gain a bit of traction and virality
column5: as shaving has little to no consequence on sexual assault.

column2: gillette actually has a pink tax on their products
column3: which means their women's razors retail at about ¬£3-4 more than the men's alternative. it's a bit rich coming from a brand who
column5: is essentially shaming their customers for not treating women correctly and it is that fact which
column7: discredited the entire campaign by stripping it of any authentic intent. in gillette's defence

column2: ‚Äú‚Ä¶yet an ember under tarnish glows‚Äù. that ember pushed me forward. for my dignity

column1: what i hadn‚Äôt expected was to feel some of those earlier emotions return to me in waves. but each time they visited
column2: they had less power. and the ember became a flickering flame

column1: the most amazing thing to me in creating this body of work
column2: was realizing that i wasn‚Äôt alone. right around the time that i was busy in my studio painting through my feelings
column3: the #metoo movement was gaining force. during the show
column4: i had women and men tell me how much they related to the emotions portrayed in the paintings.  a few with tears in their eyes. it‚Äôs not that i thought i was the only one with these feelings
column5: obviously. it was that when i allowed myself to be vulnerable
column6: others felt safe to share their vulnerabilities.‚†Ä

column1: when we feel safe to share
column2: dialogue begins. we open safe spaces to discuss difficult topics. and that allows for healing to begin.‚†Ä

column1: all 13 paintings were part of my solo show ‚Äúpassages‚Äù last march
column2: at the chapel gallery. each portrayed a deep emotion i experienced in finding my voice during my journey from pain to healing. but this is not the end of my story. i have so much more to learn.‚†Ä

column1: every time i sit at my canvas
column2: i strive to portray human emotion. from exhilaration to the deepest sadness. i feel that by honouring all our emotions we give them space to be

column1: 52235;instagram;2019-02-01 11:06:19;FALSE;"about five years ago i started working on this comic. i made this prologue in 2015. the prologue is directly based on the news stories with words and quotes coming directly from people interviewed and newscasters. i got stuck because i couldn't decide how i wanted the format of the story to be.  since meeting megumi i've started to work on it again. helping her with her comic inspired me to revisit it. she bounces ideas off me and asks me to check her drafts or character motivations
column2: etc. she's really good at paneling and composition so i'm def gonna ask her for help with that later. i never thought this comic would feel so relevant ...with trump's wall and the #metoo movement
column3: i'm even more compelled to finish it soon. i've finished the definitive outline of the story and main characters' motivations and emotional investment and it feels really cohesive. now to work on the details. i'm hoping to finish this year. please check out the prologue linked below and stay tuned. link also in bio. #dianathehuntressofbusdrivers #comics #art #instart #comicbooks #manga #independentcomics #pulpfiction #pulpmagazine #comicart #metoo #metoomovement

52428;instagram;2019-02-01 06:18:17;FALSE;i've had this thought rolling around in my brain. it has nothing to do with the picture üòÇ just enjoy! i have been separating people into two categories
column2: those who have experienced trauma and those who haven't. but perhaps trauma isn't so black and white. i grew up in a ""good"" family. i have two parents
column4: i can't join the #metoo movement. those things haven't touched my life. i have believed for a long time that i didn't belong in conversations about recovering from trauma. having panic attacks for no apparent reason does not constitute trauma. that's just being overdramatic. but i'm beginning to realize trauma is more of a spectrum. there are those people who have suffered horrifically at the hands of those who were supposed to protect them
column5: or there's that surprising kind of trauma from a freak accident that changes a life forever
column7: and there are people like me who are irrationally terrified of parking lots. it took losing my best friend to realize that my fear and sadness had robbed me of my ability to be even half a person. but i had to stop ignoring it
column8: i had to stop denying that i was in pain. and
column10: it wasn't therapy or a even my good friends that pulled me out. it was the constant and reassuring hand of jesus christ. one day at a time he reached for me
column11: i'm sad to say some days i shoved it away to do things my way but there he was again
column12: reaching for me. if you're in pain and you find yourself shoving it aside because ""well
column13: so and so has it way worse"" stop it. please. tell a friend. write it down. and don't stop taking it to god. even if you wake up tomorrow and the sun doesn't shine out your butt and you're not ready to take on that scary parking lot. he won't leave you hanging.

this is just one of many things my stalker has done to harass me and my loved ones.
i‚Äôve had many of you reach out and ask how to get justice or how to deal with these types of actions. at times it can feel inescapable because there is no safety.
the best resource i can refer you to right now is victimsofacrime.org. the link is in my bio!

bukan sekadar ada umbrella act lalu persoalan kekerasan seksual selesai. perancis yang telah mengatur tentang sanksi kriminal pelecehan seksual di tempat kerja menunjukkan pejabat dunia christine lagarde yang juga mantan menkeu pransis pernah menjadi korban pelecehan seksual bersama puluhan mantan perempuan terkemuka prancis lainnya. atau gerakan #metoo yang kini mendunia menunjukkan bahwa hukum di negara-negara tersebut tidak mampu menghentikan kekerasan seksual.

column1: i have the honor tonight of designing a tablescape for hear our stories by @upsetting_rape at @motorhousebaltimore. this edition of hear our stories is about celebrating black victim-survivors. this table was a special one to design. i will be honoring my mother
column6: and myself through a light meal dedicated to active healing in 2019. as with all of my tablescapes there will be symbolism to each element.

column1: there will be cacao butter chia cornbread made with @eatsoular cacao butter (symbolizing wealth as nourishing and healthy relationships with our bodies and ourselves) and a remix of the classic rice and black-eyed peas dish hoppin‚Äô john (with the black eyed peas symbolizing the exploration of restorative justice in domestic violence
column2: brown rice to symbolize prosperity in the path of healing
column3: and adobo chiles to represent the concept of thriving versus surviving on the very linear path of healing). for even lighter nourishment i will also have my smoke on the water broth for sipping. it is a vegan broth i make with applewood smoked sun tea and garlic i ferment for 15 days. all foods served are vegan. please join us for this very special night of fellowship and reflection. #‚ù§Ô∏è#notalone #metoo #comestibledesign #fooddesign #tablescape #blackhealing #healingfoods";en;#Repost

column1: 52849;instagram;2019-01-31 23:34:11;FALSE;"here‚Äôs a throwback to a painting i did a couple of years back as an outlet on a personal note. .
in college and for a while after
column2: i was caught in the midst of some very toxic relationships
column3: the most prominent one being my romantic interest of on and off a couple of years. the emotional toll it took on me took a long while to recover from
column4: and the physical aspects of it made the intimate parts of dating hard for me to even consider or be ok with. .

column1: i guess the silver lining of the bad experiences were that i took a long inward look at myself and what i wanted and needed in a partner
column2: and i refused to settle for anything less. i also learned that my body is mine no matter how bad someone else may want it. it‚Äôs ok to say no to the too eager first date who wants a kiss directly afterwards. it‚Äôs ok to turn down and distance yourself from the one time date that hinted at wanting far more than i was willing to give. i owe physical favors to no one
column3: and that is that. a plate of food at a restaurant should not be considered the toll you pay to get to hop in the sack with someone. for a real and wholesome relationship
column4: there‚Äôs a lot more to it than that.

column1: i‚Äôm in a much better place now with a much sweeter
column3: and more respectful partner who doesn‚Äôt press boundaries or force anything on me that i don‚Äôt want.

column3: and more respectful paner who doesn‚Äôt press boundaries or force anything on me that i don‚Äôt want.

column1: 52962;instagram;2019-01-31 21:53:31;FALSE;"#metoo | last monday i was sexually assaulted on the tube during the am rush hour. whilst standing on one of the  most overcrowded trains i have ever been on (and i've been getting the tube for 11 years!) a man completely took advantage of the situation and of me.
and i did nothing. literally nothing. partly because i was pretty much stuck in a position i couldn't move from but mostly because i was terrified
column2: of both the situation and of what the fifty commuters around me would think if i suddenly reacted to it

column1: how insane is that? a man is molesting me in public and i didn't feel like i could or should do anything about it. it was only after it had happened and the fear had subsided that i realised how angry i was and how i should have done something about it

column3: i reported it to the british transport police. i had been dubious
column4: wondering what they would actually be able to do about it. but im so glad i did. the btp take all forms of sexual assault extremely seriously. they were supportive on the phone and i was able to give a very detailed description of him and of exactly what happened.

column1: it's so important people do this
column2: previously we haven't and that's why the assault continues
column3: because people think they can get away with it.

column1: i was shocked to learn that not all tube lines have cctv. did you know that?? and according to the officer i spoke to
column2: rush hour is the most common time for a woman to be sexually assaulted on the tube because the culprit knows ""they can get away with it."" so please
column5: or if you see it happening to someone else
column6: please please please report it to the british transport police. you can either text 61016 or call 0800 40 50 40. don''t feel like it is a waste of time. it could stop another person from being assaulted.

column1: i almost didn't post about this. i felt a bit like it's not something i should discuss. especially on social media. but  screw that! people need to be made aware that this is happening
column2: all the time! oh and @transportforlondon you need to get cctv cameras on all tubes and at all stations!";;en;#METOO;@transportforlondon;;;;0;;hannahbananablog;H A N N A H üçå B A N A N A;;0;False;135;0;0;888;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/553c235ac2ea478a0da0d606771e2c1c/5D151A46/t51.2885-15/e35/50163135_808003439534394_8887744959372824965_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"#metoo | last monday i was sexually assaulted on the tube during the am rush hour. whilst standing on one of the  most overcrowded trains i have ever been on (and i have been getting the tube for 11 years!) a man completely took advantage of the situation and of me.
